title: For Sale/Trade:  Percussion converted Revolutionary War Era De Culle .69 cal musket
postcontent:
This is your chance to own a 200 + year old weapon. It was a revolutionary war period flint lock that was converted to percussion. This gun has been in my family since the 1940's. 

The name De Culle marked on the lock. The gun is clearly 1777 french patterned model similar to a Charlieville either Dragoon or Navy. I could only find 2 examples of a De Culle weapon on line. One was a Lock that was by itself and no info, the other was a converted 1822 pistol that was considerably newer with more markings. The full name on those samples where Mre Rle De Culle whereas this gun is Mre ump De Culle.

It is a .69 Cal. It was definitely a Flintlock when it was manufactured. The barrel length 40.5" overall 55.5 barrel tip to top of butt plate. There is a cheek cut on the left side of the butt stock and there is the two finger grip ridges behind the trigger guard which where both constant with the 1777 French pattern. Further, the brass fittings including trigger guard are consistent with the Navy versions of that arm. Finally there is a casting mark on the inside of the front barrel band that appears to me to be 1780 or 1790 followed by 140, but it is quite eroded.  

We were told it was converted to percussion by the confederacy for the civil war. There appears to be inspector stamps (IC) on the lock, outside of the trigger guard, the front barrel band and very lightly visible on the stock just behind the brass lock screw backing plate (I am not sure what that part is called). 

The hammer and hammer retaining screw are not original as they were not on the gun when i got it. In the 70's I adapted a Springfield type hammer to get it fire-able.

I have included a good many detail pictures. I have these are available in high res. If you need others let me know.

Face to face transaction only. 
Illinois residents must have FOID and all laws will be obeyed.

title: For Sale:  Walther PPK Clone WELT WAFFEN W Germany FEG 7.65 32 acp
postcontent:
This is a very solid pistol marked WELT WAFFEN W GERMANY 7.65 Browning. It is similar in form to a WALTHER PPK but was manufactured by FEG, a well-reputed Hungarian company that improved on the Walther design by adding a firing pin block safety. It has a steel slide and titanium alloy frame. Built to last a lifetime.

The pistol measures about 7 inches long and 4.5 high. I have big hands and it's a very comfortable gun to hold and shoot. 7.65 Browning is the same as 32 acp which is a nice round for range shooting and is not to be sneezed at. (Hitler committed suicide with this round.) The European guns generally prefer precision Euro ammo made by companies like Fiocchi or Prvi Partisan which are excellent and cheap rather than Winchester or other American ammo that can be a hair longer.

This gun looks superficially rough but it only needs a little clean-up work to look really nice. There is a bit of holster wear (extremely superficial pitting near the front of the slide) and some fleabites on the front of the grip. It will greatly improve if it's stripped and re-blacked which is not difficult. It currently has silver coating on the exposed part of the barrel inside the slide opening that looks okay but should be stripped as well.  

I used it as a range gun and it was always very reliable and accurate. I haven't been to the range lately so it can probably use a little cleaning and fresh grease on the rails.

It is very easy to take down. It has the same kind of pull-down trigger guard as a Makarov then the slide lifts up and off. It's a low maintenance gun and with a little clean-up will be a very cool reliable pistol worthy of James Bond.

Nice cloth gun case is included.

Franchi Spas 12

No Box.
Cash or Bank Cashier’s Check only.

The Franchi SPAS-12 is a combat shotgun manufactured by Italian firearms company Franchi from 1979 to 2000.  Only five percent (about 1,850) of the estimated SPAS-12 shotguns manufactured were imported into the United States. The SPAS-12 is a dual-mode shotgun, adjustable for semi-automatic or pump-action operation. 
The SPAS 12 was designed to function primarily as a semi-automatic firearm, with the pump-action mode used to reliably fire low-pressure ammunition such as tear gas rounds or less-lethal bean bags. The firing mode is switched by pressing a button under the fore grip and sliding the fore grip slightly forwards or backwards until it clicks into position. 
The SPAS-12 has a magazine cut-off feature, which prevents loading a new round from the internal magazine when the gun is cycled. This allows the operator to load a specialized round into the chamber without firing the entire magazine first. A unique feature of the SPAS-12 was the hook on folding-stock variants. This hook could be rotated in 90-degree increments, so it would fit under the user's forearm when the stock was extended. With the stock supported under the forearm the gun could theoretically be fired with one hand, allowing the user to fire around cover or use their support hand for other tasks.

Excellent plus with 98% plus of the original blue finish overall with only a hint of holster high spot wear overall.
